Such families showed their pride of ancestry in the host of ancestors surrounding their atrium ¹² and paraded at their funerals ¹³5 and even their unworthy members seem to have retained no small share of popular reverence14. Side by side with these are the houses that had corne to the front in the revolution, as the descendants of Agrippa ¹⁵, Pollio ¹⁶, and Taurus ¹⁷, or those since ennobled like the Vitellii ¹⁸ ; while a Sulpicius Quiririus ¹⁹ under Augustus, or a Curtius Rufus ²⁰ under Tibe- nus, are examples of men of the people rising to rank by personal energy. Such decay of old families as belongs to this stage, seems thus to be traceable to little else but their own hideous gluttony and luxury2¹‚1 and ruinous ostentation ²²3 to their vast parks and villas which helped to make the food of Italy dependent on wind and wave23, and which had seemed, even in the time of Horace, to be crowding the fish out of the sea and leaving on land few acres for the plough ²⁴.

It must be borne in mind that senatorial families must have ranged in wealth from the bare census of a million H.S.2⁵‚ exceeded by many knights and even freedmen, to the 400 millions of an augur Lentulus ²⁶. The greatest, with their vast estates and slave-gangs in Italy and the provinces, and often with great sums employed in trade and usury, through indulgent administration of prohibitory laws ἱῖ, lived on aprincely scale, and rewarded their host of retainers with almost royal munifi- cence²⁸.
